  "text": "Dead value information (DVI) is introduced my Martin et al. [CITATION_1] which is calculated by the compiler and passed to the processor to help with early register releasing. DVI can be passed via new explicit DVI (E-DVI) instructions which contain a bit-mask indicating the registers released, or implicitly on certain instructions. Procedure calls and returns use implicit DVI (I-DVI) such that when a dynamic call or return is committed the caller-saved registers are released early because the calling conventions implicitly state that they will not be live. The scheme we present in this paper also releases caller-saved registers at procedure boundaries using I-DVI. Once again, with this scheme by Martin et al. precise exceptions and interrupts are not maintained.",
